{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585858","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585858"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:20:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:20:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15025"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15025","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15025"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.59,0.04,0.2,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7713"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115449"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7713","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7713"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15025"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97452"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8121"},{"type":"tags","id":"9850"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18842"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18845"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115449","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115449"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EPotassium is the main intracellular cation and its concentration gradient across cell membranes is crucial for normal cellular function. Understanding the effects of potassium imbalance is essential for clinical practice.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the physiological effects of altered plasma potassium concentration?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hypokalaemia causes decreased muscle excitability","Hyperkalaemia causes ventricular fibrillation and cardiac conduction blocks","Hypokalaemia causes vasoconstriction","Hyperkalaemia increases neuromuscular excitability","Hypokalaemia has no effect on cardiac conduction"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is that \u003Cstrong\u003Ehyperkalaemia causes ventricular fibrillation and cardiac conduction blocks\u003C/strong\u003E. This is a life-threatening complication of elevated potassium levels that requires urgent intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypokalaemia causes decreased muscle excitability\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as initially hypokalaemia increases muscle excitability, though weakness can develop later. \u003Cstrong\u003EHypokalaemia causes vasoconstriction\u003C/strong\u003E is also incorrect since hypokalaemia actually causes vasodilation. \u003Cstrong\u003EHyperkalaemia increases neuromuscular excitability\u003C/strong\u003E is wrong because hyperkalaemia decreases membrane excitability, leading to weakness. \u003Cstrong\u003EHypokalaemia has no effect on cardiac conduction\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as hypokalaemia decreases conduction velocity and can cause U waves on ECG.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBoth high and low potassium levels can have serious effects on cardiac, neuromuscular, and vascular function. The effects are primarily due to changes in membrane potential and cellular excitability.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Hyperkalaemia causes cardiac conduction disturbances and can lead to ventricular fibrillation","Hypokalaemia initially increases muscle excitability but can progress to weakness","Potassium imbalances significantly impact cardiac, vascular, and neuromuscular function"],"references":["Weaver CM. Potassium and health. Adv Nutr. 2013 May 1;4(3):368S-77S. doi: 10.3945/an.112.003533. PMID: 23674806; PMCID: PMC3650509.","Simon LV, Hashmi MF, Farrell MW. Hyperkalemia. 2023 Sep 4. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 29261936.","He FJ, MacGregor GA. Beneficial effects of potassium on human health. Physiol Plant. 2008 Aug;133(4):725-35. doi: 10.1111/j.1399-3054.2007.01033.x. PMID: 18724413.","Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97452"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15025"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97452","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97452"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T19:01:50+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T19:02:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7713"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115449"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Le